  abstract = {A capacitance sensor has been developed for measuring time-averaged void fractions in two-phase pipe flow. The electrode configuration consists of a helical cross capacitor in which is placed a dielectric tube. To render edge effects negligible guard electrodes are used. For annular and dispersed flow configurations theoretical calibration curves are derived by solving the Laplace equation. The thickness of the wall of the dielectric tube appeared to be a very important design parameter. For annular and stratified flow experimental curves are presented. For many practical flow situations the time-averaged void fraction can be determined with an absolute accuracy of 卤0.03. Due to the relatively long axial extension local void fraction measurements are not possible and for mixed flow patterns, such as intermittent flow with frothy slugs, the accuracy is less. The time-varying output signal is useful for flow pattern identification. The sensor is easy to machine and only a standard capacitance meter is needed.},
}

